### 1941 Film by Jules White

One might assume that the annals of cinematic history are reserved for profound epics and groundbreaking artistry. Then again, sometimes they merely document the enduring appeal of men hitting each other with pastries. Such is the case with *[In the Sweet Pie and Pie](/In_the_Sweet_Pie_and_Pie)*, a 1941 cinematic excursion into the realm of organized chaos, meticulously orchestrated by director [Jules White](/Jules_White). This particular short subject, hardly a magnum opus but undeniably a milestone for its stars, was brought to life from a screenplay by [Clyde Bruckman](/Clyde_Bruckman), based on a story concept by [Ewart Adamson](/Ewart_Adamson). The production itself was overseen by [Jules White](/Jules_White), ensuring his signature brand of controlled pandemonium.

The film prominently features the inimitable talents of [Moe Howard](/Moe_Howard), [Larry Fine](/Larry_Fine), and [Curly Howard](/Curly_Howard), the core triumvirate of [The Three Stooges](/The_Three_Stooges), whose very names conjure images of eye-pokes and guttural exclamations. Supporting their antics, a roster of familiar faces from the era includes [Dorothy Appleby](/Dorothy_Appleby), [Mary Ainslee](/Mary_Ainslee), [Ethelreda Leopold](/Ethelreda_Leopold), [Richard Fiske](/Richard_Fiske), [Vernon Dent](/Vernon_Dent), [Symona Boniface](/Symona_Boniface), [Eddie Laughton](/Eddie_Laughton), [John Tyrrell](/John_Tyrrell_(actor)), and [Geneva Mitchell](/Geneva_Mitchell). The visual narrative, captured with characteristic efficiency, was the work of cinematographer [George Meehan](/George_Meehan), while the final assemblage of comedic beats was handled by editor [Jerome Thoms](/Jerome_Thoms).

Distributed by the venerable [Columbia Pictures](/Columbia_Pictures), a studio that became virtually synonymous with the Stooges' output, *[In the Sweet Pie and Pie](/In_the_Sweet_Pie_and_Pie)* premiered to American audiences on October 16, 1941. Clocking in at a brisk 17 minutes and 28 seconds, it delivered precisely the kind of rapid-fire gags and physical comedy that audiences expected. Originating from the [United States](/United_States), the film was presented entirely in [English](/English), ensuring that the intricate dialogue (or rather, the grunts and shouts) was universally understood by its intended demographic.

This particular entry holds the distinction of being the 58th [short subject](/Short_film) in the extensive series released by [Columbia Pictures](/Columbia_Pictures) starring the iconic American [slapstick](/Slapstick) comedy team, [The Three Stooges](/The_Three_Stooges). Over their prolific career, [Moe Howard](/Moe_Howard), [Larry Fine](/Larry_Fine), and [Curly Howard](/Curly_Howard) would release an astonishing 190 shorts for the studio, cementing their legacy in comedic history between 1934 and 1959. *[In the Sweet Pie and Pie](/In_the_Sweet_Pie_and_Pie)* stands as a testament to their unwavering commitment to absurdity, a small cog in a much larger, remarkably durable machine.

### Plot

The narrative of *[In the Sweet Pie and Pie](/In_the_Sweet_Pie_and_Pie)*, if one can call such a contrivance a "narrative," unfurls with the introduction of Tiska, Taska, and Baska Jones. These three women, portrayed as assertive pillars of high society, find themselves in a precarious financial situation, specifically, on the verge of inheriting a substantial fortune. The catch, a rather inconvenient one, is that this inheritance is strictly contingent upon their marital status by a very specific, rapidly approaching deadline. Their pre-existing fiancés, charmingly named [Tom, Dick and Harry](/Tom,_Dick_and_Harry) (a clear nod to the famous phrase, because subtlety was clearly not the goal), are unfortunately indisposed. Their commitment to romance evidently takes a backseat to their deployment with the Fleet in Honolulu, leaving the women in a rather desperate lurch.

Enter Diggins, the women's shrewd, if morally flexible, lawyer. He proposes a rather ingenious, albeit ethically dubious, scheme: to secure their inheritance, the women should marry three conveniently condemned inmates. These unfortunates are identified as the infamous Mushroom Murder Gang, a trio of hapless individuals portrayed, naturally, by [The Three Stooges](/The_Three_Stooges). The plan, as conceived by Diggins and embraced by the Jones sisters, is elegantly simple: marry the convicts, collect the inheritance, and then, with the inmates safely executed, they would be free to resume their original engagements with their Honolulu-bound lovers. A perfectly rational solution, if one possesses a soul made of pure granite.

The Stooges, now begrudgingly wed to the Jones sisters, are subsequently deposited in Hang-em'-all Prison, facing an imminent execution by hanging. One can almost hear the cosmic sigh of relief from the women. However, the universe, in its infinite capacity for ironic twists, intervenes. A last-minute reprieve arrives, a bureaucratic miracle, absolving them of any guilt in the Mushroom murders. With their names cleared, the Stooges are abruptly freed, much to the universe's amusement and the Jones sisters' utter dismay. The women, having already begun to revel in their newfound (and anticipated) status as wealthy widows, are confronted with the inconvenient reality of their living, breathing, and incredibly boorish husbands asserting their conjugal rights within the women's opulent household. This unexpected turn of events shatters their carefully constructed post-widowhood bliss.

What follows is an excruciatingly polite, yet ultimately doomed, attempt by the Jones sisters to integrate their new husbands into the hallowed halls of high society. They are convinced, with ample justification, that the Stooges are utterly ill-equipped for such refinement, a belief that proves to be an understatement. Yet, the Stooges, recognizing the precariousness of their marital status – and likely, the potential for further pie-related incidents if they fail – diligently strive, in their own uniquely catastrophic way, to meet the impossible expectations imposed upon them. Their efforts, predictably, culminate in a social gathering that swiftly descends into utter chaos, a symphony of misplaced decorum and accidental destruction orchestrated by the Stooges. Diggins, the architect of this matrimonial farce, attempts to discredit [Moe Howard](/Moe_Howard) during the debacle, only for his machinations to spectacularly backfire, adding another layer of slapstick humiliation to the proceedings.

In the face of Diggins's renewed threats of annulment, which would, of course, divest them of their hard-won inheritance, the Jones sisters make a rather surprising, if pragmatic, decision. They defiantly reject Diggins's influence and, choosing to prioritize their financial security over social standing (or perhaps, finally succumbing to the Stooges' peculiar charm), opt to retain their marriages. In a final, glorious display of solidarity and collective exasperation, the guests, having witnessed the entire charade, join forces with the Stooges. Together, they mete out a fitting punishment to the conniving Diggins, subjecting him to a thoroughly deserved, and undoubtedly messy, pie-filled retribution, bringing the film to its predictable, yet satisfyingly chaotic, conclusion.

### Production Notes

*[In the Sweet Pie and Pie](/In_the_Sweet_Pie_and_Pie)* was brought to life on the [Columbia Pictures](/Columbia_Pictures) backlot during a concentrated period of filming, specifically between April 30 and May 3, 1941. This efficient production schedule was typical for the studio's short subjects, maximizing resources and ensuring a steady stream of content for eager audiences.

The film, as was often the custom for Stooges shorts, peppered its dialogue and scenarios with timely cultural references, allowing it to resonate with contemporary viewers. These nods to popular culture of the era include:

*   [Moe Howard](/Moe_Howard)'s enigmatic declaration, "I am [The Shadow](/The_Shadow)," serves as a direct parody of the popular 1940 [Columbia radio serial](/Serial_(radio_and_television)) of the same name. This line, delivered with Moe's characteristic sternness, would have been instantly recognizable to audiences familiar with the mysterious crime fighter.
*   The character "Bill Stein," who provides a rather dramatic "jerk-by-jerk" description of the impending hanging of the "Mushroom Murder Mob," is a thinly veiled, humorous jab at the real-life, celebrated sportscaster [Bill Stern](/Bill_Stern). Stern was known for his flamboyant and often exaggerated commentary, a style ripe for comedic imitation.
*   The very title of the film, *[In the Sweet Pie and Pie](/In_the_Sweet_Pie_and_Pie)*, is a clever and rather obvious [play on words](/Play_on_words), referencing the familiar old gospel song, "[In the Sweet By and By](/In_the_Sweet_By_and_By)." This lighthearted manipulation of a well-known phrase immediately signals the film's comedic intent. Similarly, the names chosen for the three society sisters—Tiska, Taska, and Baska—are a direct and whimsical allusion to the popular children's song, "[A-Tisket, A-Tasket](/A-Tisket,_A-Tasket)." Furthering the trend, [Curly Howard](/Curly_Howard)'s somewhat nonsensical comment to Moe, "I hear a rhipsody," is a clear comedic corruption of the 1940 musical hit, "[I Hear a Rhapsody](/1940_in_music)." These allusions, while perhaps lost on modern audiences, provided a layer of immediate comedic recognition for the film's original viewers.
*   As previously noted, the fiancés of the Jones sisters are given the generic yet instantly recognizable names of [Tom, Dick and Harry](/Tom,_Dick_and_Harry), a ubiquitous phrase used to refer to any random group of people.

The production of *[In the Sweet Pie and Pie](/In_the_Sweet_Pie_and_Pie)*, like many [Three Stooges](/The_Three_Stooges) shorts, often relied on the practical efficiency of [recycled footage](/List_of_Three_Stooges_recycled_shorts) from previous productions. This judicious reuse of existing film allowed the studio to stretch budgets and production timelines, a common practice in the era of rapid-fire short film output:

*   A notable sequence, specifically the dancing lesson, was directly lifted from the 1935 Stooges short, *[Hoi Polloi](/Hoi_Polloi_(1935_film))*. This allowed for a quick and cost-effective way to depict the Stooges' predictably disastrous attempts at refined movement.
*   Footage depicting the cell block scenes was later repurposed and re-used in the 1946 Stooges short, *[Beer Barrel Polecats](/Beer_Barrel_Polecats)*, demonstrating the long-term utility of well-shot set pieces.
*   Several key shots from the climactic pie fight sequence in *[In the Sweet Pie and Pie](/In_the_Sweet_Pie_and_Pie)* would later make an appearance in the 1947 film, *[Pest Man Wins](/Pest_Man_Wins)*, underscoring the timeless appeal and reusability of a good pie in the face.

Tragically, *[In the Sweet Pie and Pie](/In_the_Sweet_Pie_and_Pie)* holds a somber distinction as the final cinematic appearance for supporting actor [Richard Fiske](/Richard_Fiske). Fiske, a familiar and often effective foil for [The Three Stooges](/The_Three_Stooges) in their shorts, had a promising career ahead of him. However, the burgeoning global conflict of [World War II](/World_War_II) intervened, and Fiske's life was tragically cut short when he was killed in action. His loss was a poignant reminder of the war's far-reaching impact, even on the seemingly frivolous world of Hollywood comedy.

### Pie Fights

The art of the pie fight, a cornerstone of [slapstick](/Slapstick) comedy, often appears effortless on screen. However, as [Larry Fine](/Larry_Fine) himself recalled, the reality behind these chaotic scenes, particularly those featured in *[In the Sweet Pie and Pie](/In_Sweet_Pie_and_Pie)*, was anything but glamorous, often bordering on the genuinely grueling.

Fine recounted the less-than-sanitary conditions that sometimes accompanied these custard-filled skirmishes: "Sometimes we would run out of pies, so the prop man would sweep up the pie goop off the floor, complete with nails, splinters, and tacks." One can only imagine the sheer dedication (or perhaps, the desperate need for a paycheck) that allowed them to continue filming under such remarkably unhygienic circumstances. It makes one wonder if a tetanus shot was a standard part of the call sheet.

Another significant challenge in perfecting the comedic timing of a pie fight was the necessity of maintaining a genuine element of surprise. The performers had to appear truly unaware that a pie was hurtling towards their face. Director [Jules White](/Jules_White), known for his shrewd methods, devised a rather mischievous solution to this problem. Fine explained the deceptive tactic: "To solve this, Jules would tell me 'Now Larry, Moe is going to smack you with a pie on the count of three.' Then Jules would tell Moe, 'Hit Larry on the count of two!' So when it came time to count, I never got to three, because Moe crowned me with a pie!" This anecdote not only illustrates the directorial cunning employed to achieve authentic reactions but also highlights the inherent trust (or perhaps, resigned acceptance) required amongst the Stooges themselves, who were often the unsuspecting victims of such calculated betrayals. The pursuit of laughter, it seems, often came with a side of unexpected dairy products and minor psychological trauma.

